Let the arithmetic sequence be denoted by $a_n$, where $a_n = a_1 + (n-1)d$ for $n \geq 1$. We are given that $a_4 = 200$ and $a_8 = 500$. Thus,
\begin{align*} \label{eq:1} a_4 &= a_1 + (4-1)d = a_1 + 3d = 200 \\ a_8 &= a_1 + (8-1)d = a_1 + 7d = 500 \end{align*}
Subtracting the first equation from the second equation, we get
\begin{align*} (a_1 + 7d) - (a_1 + 3d) &= 500 - 200 \\ 4d &= 300 \\ d &= \frac{300}{4} \\ d &= 75 \end{align*}
Substituting $d=75$ into the first equation $a_1 + 3d = 200$, we get
\begin{align*} a_1 + 3(75) &= 200 \\ a_1 + 225 &= 200 \\ a_1 &= 200 - 225 \\ a_1 &= -25 \end{align*}
We want to find $a_6$, which is $a_1 + 5d$. We have $a_1 = -25$ and $d = 75$, so
\begin{align*} a_6 &= a_1 + 5d \\ &= -25 + 5(75) \\ &= -25 + 375 \\ &= 350 \end{align*}
Thus, the sixth term is $350$.

