Let $x = 18^\circ$. Then we want to compute $\sin^3 x + \sin^2 x$.
We have
\begin{align*} \sin^3 x + \sin^2 x &= \sin^2 x (\sin x + 1) \\ &= \sin^2 x (\sin x + 1) \end{align*}
We know that $\sin 18^\circ = \frac{\sqrt{5} - 1}{4}$.
Then
\begin{align*} \sin^2 18^\circ &= \left( \frac{\sqrt{5} - 1}{4} \right)^2 \\ &= \frac{(\sqrt{5} - 1)^2}{16} \\ &= \frac{5 - 2\sqrt{5} + 1}{16} \\ &= \frac{6 - 2\sqrt{5}}{16} \\ &= \frac{3 - \sqrt{5}}{8} \end{align*}
Also,
\begin{align*} \sin^3 18^\circ + \sin^2 18^\circ &= \sin^2 18^\circ (\sin 18^\circ + 1) \\ &= \frac{3 - \sqrt{5}}{8} \left( \frac{\sqrt{5} - 1}{4} + 1 \right) \\ &= \frac{3 - \sqrt{5}}{8} \left( \frac{\sqrt{5} - 1 + 4}{4} \right) \\ &= \frac{3 - \sqrt{5}}{8} \left( \frac{\sqrt{5} + 3}{4} \right) \\ &= \frac{(3 - \sqrt{5})(\sqrt{5} + 3)}{32} \\ &= \frac{3\sqrt{5} + 9 - 5 - 3\sqrt{5}}{32} \\ &= \frac{4}{32} \\ &= \frac{1}{8} \end{align*}
Thus, $\sin^3 18^\circ + \sin^2 18^\circ = \frac{1}{8}$.

Final Answer: The final answer is $\boxed{\frac{1}{8}}$

